# Project Rules: linked flow AI

You are working on linked flow AI, a bilingual AI-powered mini tool that rewrites user text into LinkedIn-ready content.

Follow these rules strictly.

---

# Tech Standards

- Use Next.js 15 with App Router.
- Use TypeScript strict mode.
- Use React Server Components by default.
- Use Client Components only when interactivity is required.
- Use Tailwind CSS and shadcn/ui.
- Use Poppins as the main font.
- Use Zod for all validation.
- Keep components small, focused, and reusable.
- Avoid unnecessary dependencies.
- Prefer simple, readable code over clever abstractions.

---

# Security Rules

- Never expose OPENAI_API_KEY to the client.
- All OpenAI calls must happen server-side only.
- Validate all incoming API payloads with Zod.
- Reject requests with invalid, empty, or oversized text.
- Do not store user-submitted text.
- Do not log full user text in production.
- Do not store personal data.
- Do not use cookies unless strictly necessary.
- Add rate limiting before calling OpenAI.
- Return safe error messages to the client.
- Never leak stack traces, API responses, tokens, or internal errors.

---

# OpenAI Usage Rules

- Use a dedicated lib/openai.ts service.
- Keep prompts controlled and deterministic.
- Do not allow the model to invent achievements, numbers, employers, certifications, or claims.
- Preserve the original meaning of the user text.
- Output must match the selected language.
- Output must match the selected tone.
- Use low-to-medium temperature.
- Set reasonable max tokens.
- Never call OpenAI if validation fails.
- Never call OpenAI if rate limit fails.

---

# Rate Limit Rules

- Enforce max 10 rewrites per IP per day.
- Enforce 30 seconds cooldown between requests per IP.
- Use Upstash Redis or another server-side rate limit provider.
- Prevent duplicate frontend submissions.
- Disable submit button while request is pending.
- Avoid repeated requests for identical unchanged text.

---

# UX Rules

- The app must work in Spanish and English.
- All labels, buttons, errors, modals, and helper texts must be translated.
- The user must accept legal terms before generating.
- The submit button must be disabled until:
  - text is valid
  - terms are accepted
  - no request is pending

- Show clear loading, success, and error states.
- Provide a copy-to-clipboard button.
- Provide a clear/reset button.
- Use responsive design for mobile, tablet, and desktop.

---

# Legal UX Rules

The footer must include modal links for:

- Terms and Conditions
- Privacy Policy
- Responsible AI Use
- Disclaimer
- Contact

Legal copy must clearly state:

- AI-generated content may be inaccurate.
- The user is responsible for reviewing before publishing.
- The app does not guarantee job, business, or reputation outcomes.
- Users must not submit confidential, private, sensitive, or third-party data.
- User input may be processed by external AI providers.
- The app is used at the user's own responsibility.

---

# Code Quality Rules

- Use named exports unless a framework convention requires default exports.
- Use descriptive variable and function names.
- Avoid files longer than necessary.
- Avoid duplicated logic.
- Extract constants to lib/constants.ts.
- Extract translations to lib/i18n.ts.
- Extract validation schemas to lib/validations.ts.
- Extract API logic to service files.
- Keep API routes thin.
- Use early returns.
- Handle all async errors safely.

---

# Styling Rules

- Use a modern premium SaaS aesthetic.
- Use clean spacing.
- Use rounded-2xl cards.
- Use subtle borders and shadows.
- Use accessible contrast.
- Use responsive layouts.
- Avoid visual clutter.
- Do not use random colors outside the design system.

---

# Accessibility Rules

- All form fields must have labels.
- Modals must be keyboard accessible.
- Buttons must have clear states.
- Use semantic HTML.
- Preserve focus states.
- Use readable font sizes.
- Avoid relying only on color to communicate errors.

---

# Performance Rules

- Keep bundle size small.
- Avoid unnecessary client components.
- Avoid unnecessary re-renders.
- Use server-side logic for API/security.
- Do not import server-only code into client components.
- Avoid heavy animations.

---

# Final Goal

Every generated change must move the project toward a secure, modern, bilingual, production-ready MVP that can be deployed on Vercel and safely use OpenAI API without unnecessary token consumption.